'''Robert George Collier Proctor''' (13 May 1868 – 6 September 1903) was an [[English people|English]] [[bibliographer]], [[librarian]], [[book collector]], and expert on [[Incunable|incunabula]] and early [[typography]].

==Early life and education==
Proctor was born in [[Budleigh Salterton]], [[Devon]], [[England]], on 13 May 1868, to Robert Proctor and Anne Tate, and was a distant relative and [[namesake]] of [[John Payne Collier]].<ref name=Johnson7>{{cite book |first=Barry |last=Johnson |title=Lost in the Alps: A Portrait of Robert Proctor, the "Great Bibliographer" and of His Career in the British Museum |page=7 |location=London |publisher=B.C. Johnson |year=1985 |oclc=17484098}}</ref> He earned a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree in [[classics]] from [[Corpus Christi College, Oxford]], in 1890. While at Oxford, where he was known for his book collection, Proctor's interest in [[antiquarian]] studies, [[archaeology]], and bibliography grew and he compiled a catalogue of incunabula and early printed books in the library collection at Corpus Christi College. Proctor continued his studies of early printing at Oxford, cataloging incunabula at the [[Bodleian Library]], [[New College, Oxford|New College]] and [[Brasenose College]].<ref name=ODNB>{{Cite ODNB |id=35621 |title=Proctor, Robert George Collier |first=Dennis E. |last=Rhodes}}</ref>

==Professional life==
Proctor joined the [[British Museum]] on 16 October 1893 as an assistant in the Department of Printed Books. He quickly became an expert on early typography and began describing every known European type [[font|fount]] used before 1520.<ref name=ODNB /><ref name=Pollard>{{cite journal |first=Alfred W. |last=Pollard |title=Robert Proctor |journal=The Library |series=2nd Series |volume=5 |issue=17 |date=January 1904 |page=15 |doi=10.1093/library/s2-V.17.1}}</ref> Proctor rearranged all of the incunabula in the British Museum geographically by place of printing in what is known today as "Proctor order" and he compiled ''An Index to the Early Printed Books in the British Museum: From the Invention of Printing to the Year 1500'' which was issued in four parts from 1898 to 1903.<ref name=ODNB /> Proctor developed a [[Greek alphabet|Greek]] [[typeface]] based on type found in the [[Complutensian Polyglot Bible]].<ref name=ODNB /> Working with [[William Morris]] at the [[Kelmscott Press]], Proctor grew interested in [[Icelandic literature]] and published translations of the [[Vápnfirðinga saga]] and the [[Laxdæla saga]] in 1902 and 1903, respectively.<ref name=ODNB /><ref>{{cite book |title=The Tale of the Weaponfirthers |others=Translated by Robert Proctor |location=Edinburgh |publisher=Printed by T. and A. Constable |year=1902 |oclc=3676154}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=The Story of the Laxdalers |others=Translated by Robert Proctor |location=London |publisher=Printed for the translator by Charles Whittingham & Company, and to be obtained at the Chiswick Press |year=1903 |url=http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=njp.32101031789330 |oclc=3004467}}</ref>

==Death==
In August 1903 Proctor began a solo walking tour in the [[Central Eastern Alps|Austrian Alps]]. He left [[Pitztal]] on 5 September without a guide and was never heard from again. In December 1903 a judge granted an order [[Declared death in absentia|presuming]] Proctor's death on 6 September of that year.<ref name=Johnson>{{cite book |first=Barry |last=Johnson |title=Lost in the Alps: A Portrait of Robert Proctor, the "Great Bibliographer" and of His Career in the British Museum |location=London |publisher=B.C. Johnson |year=1985 |oclc=17484098}}</ref> His friend, [[Sydney Cockerell]], speculated that Proctor may have committed [[suicide]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Robert Proctor, William Morris and the Mysterious Death of 'the great bibliographer' |work=Special Collections and Archives (SCOLAR) |publisher=Cardiff University |date=11 June 2013 |url=http://scolarcardiff.wordpress.com/2013/06/11/robert-proctor-william-morris-and-the-mysterious-death-of-the-great-bibliographer/ |accessdate=12 January 2014}}</ref>

==Legacy==
After Proctor's death a memorial fund was established and used to collect and publish (in 1905) his ''Bibliographical Essays''. The fund also provided for the compilation and publication of the three remaining parts of Proctor's index of early printed books covering the years 1501 to 1520. Even today, some large collections of incunabula are arranged in "Proctor order" ("This means that the books are arranged and described in order of country of origin, then of town, then of printer, in chronological order").<ref name=ODNB />

