'''William Wymond Walkem''' (June 25, 1850 &ndash; September 23, 1919<ref>{{cite web |url=http://vancouver.ca/commsvcs/nonmarketoperations/mountainview/burials/wa.htm |title=Mountain View Cemetery |publisher=City of Vancouver |accessdate=2009-11-02}}</ref>) was a physician, author and political figure in [[British Columbia]], Canada. He represented [[South Nanaimo]] in the [[Legislative Assembly of British Columbia]] from 1894 to 1898.<ref name="gemmill"/>

He was born in [[Montreal]], the son of Charles Walkem, and was educated at [[McGill University]],<ref name="gemmill"/> graduating in 1873. While a student, he worked as a reporter for Montreal newspapers. After graduating, Walkem went to [[United Kingdom|Britain]] and tried unsuccessfully to join [[Carlism|Carlist]] supporters fighting in Spain. He then returned to Canada as a private secretary to his brother, [[George Anthony Walkem|George Anthony]]. Walkem was editor of the Victoria ''Daily Standard'' for a time.<ref name="archive">{{cite web |url=http://www.library.ubc.ca/spcoll/AZ/PDF/WY/Walkem_William_Wymond.pdf |title=William Wymond Walkem, 1850-1919 |publisher=University of British Columbia |accessdate=2009-11-02}}</ref> He served as inspector for [[British Columbia Penitentiary]] and was a [[coroner]] for the province from 1878 to 1895. Walkem was married twice: to Edith Moyle in 1875 and later to Minnie Brown. He ran unsuccessfully for a seat in the assembly in 1890.<ref name="gemmill">{{cite book |url=http://www.canadiana.org/view/32962/0394 |title=The Canadian parliamentary companion, 1897 |last=Gemmill |first=John A |date=1897 |page=377 |accessdate=2009-11-02}}</ref> Walkem was defeated by [[Ralph Smith (Canadian politician)|Ralph Smith]] when he ran for reelection in 1898.<ref>*{{cite encyclopedia |last = Leier |first = Mark |title = Ralph Smith |encyclopedia = [[Dictionary of Canadian Biography Online]] |date = 1998 |url = http://www.biographi.ca/009004-119.01-e.php?&id_nbr=7711
  |accessdate=2009-11-02}}</ref>

Walkem wrote ''Stories of early British Columbia'', published in 1914.

